 have hit a zenith with 2nd Edition AD&amp;D, which, if run right, tended to mitigate against &quot;Monty Haul&quot; campaigns and &quot;powergaming&quot;.  TSR refocused itself on more roleplaying aspects of the game, and developed campaign material that was more about roleplaying than game mechanics.<br><br>However, the market wasn't going in that direction.  The demographic who had been buying TSR products were now snarfing up Magic cards like there was no tomorrow instead of TSR products and TSR went under, only to get bought by Wizards of the Coast.  And WotC capitulated to the lowest common denominator in its release of Dungeons &amp; Dragons 3rd Edition.  Want to be a halfling wizard-paladin?  Sure!  Want that class with no behavior restrictions?  Sure!  Every thing I'd heard people whine about in my ten years playing in my partner's AD&amp;D campaign, every little restriction players didn't like, WotC removed in 3rd Edition.<br><br>When I heard about and got EverQuest, I thought maybe some of those problems wouldn't exist.  Many of the 'rules' are hardcoded: no halfling wizard-paladins, for example.  I found, within two days, I was wrong.  It was as if every bad roleplayer I'd ever run across in real life had cloned him- (or more rarely, her-)self a hundred times.  So I moved to Sullon Zek, before Firiona Vie opened up, figuring roleplay might be better: Evil was, by necessity, opposed to Good.  But SZ has its own unique problems, which I could do an entire thread on.  Still, I was right in my basic premise.  When Firiona Vie opened, I moved over and haven't gone back.  But there are problems.  I get asked for sows on a daily basis, for example.<br><br>Maybe roleplaying is dead.  Maybe it's dying.  I hope it can be recovered from the people whose idea of roleplaying is slapping down their Force of Nature to beat up your Mahamoti Djinn.<br><br>Lasgalen, recovering Magic: The Gathering addict <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/urobingoodfellow.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Robin Goodfellow</A> at: 1/16/02 5:03:25 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=valquisssilverpalm>Valquiss Silverpalm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 169<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/16/02 5:08:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=242.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Roleplaying's in dire straits</span><hr size=1> Some people aren't going to like me saying this, perhaps, but EQ is not now and never has been or will be the best platform for real role-playing.  It's a stradegy, fantasy, action game with elements of role-play.  I happen to like the elements of RP and that's why I'm here to get as much as possible, but to expect pure RP here is a tad unrealistic.  Go to a consent-based, free-form Mush.  I play on one of those also.  Now that is pure RP.  It is certainly not dead.<br><br>Valquiss <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ukan1301.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kan1301</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 37<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/16/02 5:12:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=242.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Roleplaying's in dire straits</span><hr size=1> Whats wrong with halfling wizard? Just because the games 20 years ago didn't have halfling wizard?  I don't mind troll wizard ogre bard if they are in game. Whats the big deal? Who said RPG has to follow old rules which made 20 years ago? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubormwarrior.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Borm Warrior</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 26<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/16/02 5:15:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=242.topic&index=3>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Roleplaying's in dire straits</span><hr size=1> I do not think the issue was a halflin wizard, per se, just the whole halfling wizard-paladin concept. It made me LOL and squirt milk through my nose just thinking about it.<br><br>Borm <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=valquisssilverpalm>Valquiss Silverpalm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 171<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/16/02 5:22:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=242.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sad.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Roleplaying's in dire straits</span><hr size=1> Oh, and Mahamoti Djinns fly whereas Forces of Nature do not.  So if you expect the one to beat up on the other, you had better throw a web on it or something.  So there.<br><br>Valquiss<br><br>(It's been many years, but my retension for this stuff is scaring me)<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=rexfelix>Rexfelix</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 41<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/16/02 6:06:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=242.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sad.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Roleplaying's in dire straits</span><hr size=1> OMG...Magic the Gathering.  I look back on that period of my life like a ex-heroin addict might reflect upon the liquid dream years of their lives.  EQ is worse than Magic tho...you don't need to leave the house to play.<br><br>I agree with you Valquiss...EQ is basically Quake or Doom with longer fights, more power-ups and a thread of continuity.  <br><br>Despite disagreeing with you on another topic Robin Goodfellow, I totally agree with you on the decline of RPG's.  I played AD&amp;D, GURPS, Shadowrun and a lot of other pen and paper games for years - with many folks who play EQ with me now as a matter of fact.  And I tend to believe that the new generations since I became involved in RPG's have too many other distractions to get involved with that are MUCH easier to follow.<br><br>Pen and paper games forced you to *gasp* read a set of rulebooks and *shudder* write out your character/dungeon/campaign ideas on paper and *faint* exercise your imagination!?!?!?  Now, everything is prepackaged and microwaveable.<br><br>I have a good analogy:  I went to buy a younger cousin a Christmas present and thought I'd get him a Lego &quot;set&quot;...you know, a big package of various pieces of Lego with which he could exercise his creativity.  I went to Wal-Mart (shudder) and what did I find?  Well, it wasn't a generic Lego set.  Rather, Lego is all &quot;themed&quot; now.  Basically, each pack of Lego only builds one thing, and even more deplorable, each package has ASSEMBLY INSTRUCTIONS.  Blasphemy!<br><br>So who the heck wants to take the time to invent a game world that people have to visualize when you can become a slave to Sony's vision?  <br><br>Hopefully things will change.<br><br>Exgamingpussy,<br><br>Rexfelix <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uhalus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Halus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 34<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/16/02 6:23:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=242.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Roleplaying's in dire straits</span><hr size=1> &gt;&gt;&gt;I think roleplaying, in general, is in trouble and has been for the past decade. &lt;&lt;&lt;<br><br>I'm sure you didn't mean for this to sound as ridiculous as it does. <br><br>For one: Role playing wasn't born when Gary Gygax published a book. Role playing is playing. <br>It's easier when you're a kid, because you get recess and stuff, and playing with Lego guys is your work. It gets more complicated as a teen or adult -- more rules, usually a lot more math, weirder people --  but still fun.<br><br>You're wrong when it comes to D&amp;D-style roleplaying. EQ, no matter what server, but especially FV, is hundreds of times more dynamic than the typical D&amp;D campaign. If I never had to look up another hit point or damage thingy from a chart I'd be happy. The personalities you meet in EQ, not to mention the lore, and the energy that goes with the game (message boards, for example<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ), add to it even more.<br><br>I can understand pining for the old days. (D&amp;D, Boot Hill, Top Secret, Aftermath(!), the Morrow Project anyone? -- make some of that coolness into an online game...). But I don't buy broad generalizations about something as nebulous as roleplaying.<br><br>Halus <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ukimayasilverbark.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kimaya Silverbark</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.alienexplorer.com/clipart/images5/wolf.pawprint2.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 52<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/16/02 6:57:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=242.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.bellsouth.net/coDataImages/bellsouthpwp/Groups/15/15568/pages/34736/Kimaya-60.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Roleplaying's in dire straits</span><hr size=1> Darn, I saw &quot;Dire Straits&quot; and thought it was another music thread.  :P<br><br>My RP groups from the late-80's onward actually tended to be light on what I considered good RP.  To be honest, half of them turned into pick-up sessions (and I wasn't interested).  There was one that was good, but when I stopped dating one of them I stopped being invited.  (I am SO glad there are more women gaming now!)<br><br>So I've joined a group again recently.  I think they all just RP themselves, and half of them I don't even like, so I stopped going.  I haven't seen things change much over time, except I'm no longer hit on via some guy's character as a general rule.  RP is still what I make of it whenever there's an opportunity to take.  EQ is a current opportunity for me, though I agree with Valquiss that it's not a pure RP environ.  Fine with me, I'm laid back.<br><br>But hey, on the topic of old joys, for Christmas I finally got the Lite Brite I always wanted!  At least those haven't changed.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>---<BR>Kimaya Silverbark<BR><BR>"I bark at that!"</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=rexfelix>Rexfelix</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 43<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/16/02 7:08:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=242.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Roleplaying's in dire straits</span><hr size=1> Whoa Lite Brite(tm)?  They still make those?  And it didn't come with an N'Sync template and instructions saying &quot;Thank you for purchasing Lite Brite.  You can use this Lite Brite to make this N'Sync sign only.&quot;  If you wish to make a Blink 182 sign, please purchase a new Lite Brite?<br><br>Rexfelix <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ugrimwyrd.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grimwyrd</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 89<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/16/02 7:10:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=242.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Roleplaying's in dire straits</span><hr size=1> Bah! Thread after thread about roleplaying, and everyone misses the point.<br><br>Quake can be a great roleplaying game!<br><br>Heck, one of my favorite roleplaying games as a kid was Frogger. Sure it was single player. And there wasn't a lot of character development. But I WAS a frog when I played that game!<br><br>Roleplaying is all about your state of mind. What matters is are YOU escaping your own life and getting into the character you're controlling.<br><br>Most of these arguments really center around what are good &quot;multi-player&quot; roleplaying games, and that's where the trouble comes in. Not everyone can get into character in the same way at the same time.<br><br>I have a very easy time envisioning myself as a human druid when I play on this server. And the reason I like this server, is because it's a lot less likely that someone will come up and ruin the illusion I've built in my mind.<br><br>When people come up and are blatantly OOC and annoying, I suddenly lose track of the fact that I'm a human druid and remember that I'm a 30-something computer-gamer that should really be doing something more useful with my tim, lol.<br><br>But that doesn't change the fact that &quot;I'm&quot; in control of whether I'm playing a role or not. Because it all comes down to each individual's ability to get into character.<br> <p>Grimwyrd Storm<BR>(Lux Aeternam)<BR>31st Human Druid of Karana<BR></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/umadrain.showPublicProfile?language=EN>madrain</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Kerran Lord</span><br>  Posts: 214<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/17/02 1:46:23 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=242.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Roleplaying's in dire straits</span><hr size=1> Eh...I disagree that EQ isn't a roleplaying game.  I very much think it's a roleplaying game.  It's just the majority of people who play it AREN'T roleplayers.  I've seen people roleplay in Half-Life and Quake II.  I imagine it's even in Quake III and UT.  Those are very much action games.  It takes people to make a roleplaying game, not a game to make a roleplaying game. <p><center><font size=+2><a href="http://pub66.ezboard.com/bmaidensfancy">Shiden Kaidan</a></font><br><font size=1><i><a href="http://www.neriak.com/">Tier'dal</a> <a href="http://interealms.com/shadowknight/">Knight</a></i></font> of the<a href="http://www.firiona-vie.com/"> Firiona Vie</a> Server<br><font color=red>@}</font><font color=green>--,---'---</font><br><i>"Let nothing stand in the way of power."</i></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ukharras.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kharras</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/17/02 3:38:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=242.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Roleplaying's in dire straits</span><hr size=1> Being an avid gamer (still play tabletop at LEAST once a week and i've got kids now), and a former small game publishing industry professional, it pains me to say this but:<br><br>Blame gaming companies for the near-extinction of RPGs.<br><br>Just a short laundry list:<br><br>Poor financial planning<br>Bad collections decisions (only an idiot doesn't sue long-term delinquent creditors, I don't care how long you have done business with them) <br>Bad Marketing<br>Bad Customer Service<br>Bad Accounting<br>Bad Public Relations (DIRECT QUOTE (to the local news from a game company rep in the city where Shawn Novak lived): &quot;No self-respecting satanist I know would play Dungeons and Dragons!&quot;)<br>Lack of basic sense (ok, look, you would have to have been a fucking idiot to not have seen UO at release and said 'It'll never work'... yet MULTIPLE game companies did)<br><br>I'm not gonna name names, but...<br>here are some excerpts:<br><br>&quot;We aren't getting into the MMORPG business because CGM[computer gaming monthly] called it a 'golden coaster' (use the CD as a coaster).&quot; (the company was being asked to license an engine and game name to a currently successful computer company)<br><br>&quot;I knew he was in bad financial shape (my distributor) but I felt bad witholding product from him or trying to collect my money; we have been friends for years&quot; (and now, you're friends in bankruptcy)<br><br>From late 1997 to mid 1998s, more than 85% of the gaming industry's distrubutors went bankrupt, owing almost tens of millions of dollars to game manufacturers and publishers. The reasons are varied... some of it was caused by the UPS strike in 1997, some was caused by CCG speculation, some was just general mismanagement. <br><br>Many publishers attempted to continue to do business as usual, not realizing they had just been dealt a mortal blow.<br><br>Add to this the MMORPG movement and the already extant CCG boom and RPGs could not survive as they existed. The game companies did not react in a realistic manner to the change in the market.<br><br>Tabletop RPGs will never actually die... but widespread published material is now a part of history. <p>Kharras Fain <BR>Janitor<BR>Crusaders of the Realm</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ukimayasilverbark.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kimaya Silverbark</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.alienexplorer.com/clipart/images5/wolf.pawprint2.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 53<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/17/02 7:50:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=242.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.bellsouth.net/coDataImages/bellsouthpwp/Groups/15/15568/pages/34736/Kimaya-60.jpg WIDT